node.text: Emily Kuhn, a former gymnast and current physics PhD student at Yale University, explains all the math behind the amazing flips and turns we see during the Olympic gymnastics competitions. Emily explains why "The Biles" tumbling routine is so difficult as well as the types of forces acting on these gymnasts every time they use the uneven bars.

node.text: The 2021 Apple iMac is an all-in-one desktop that is powerful, yet pretty. It's lightweight and colorful, and once you plug it in you are ready to go.  However, some quirky annoyances and a few needed upgrades will add some extra dollar signs to the price tag. WIRED's @julianchokkattu has more details about the completely redesigned iMac. Tap the link in our bio to read the full review.

node.title: Apple's Colorful New iMac Pairs Beauty With Brawn

Check the link in bio for the full video.

Across 15 eastern states, the same ritual is underway. Billions of cicadas are emerging this week from Brood X—a population of three separate species (two from the genus Magicicada) that emerge from the ground at the same time. There are a dozen broods of 17-year cicadas and three broods of 13-year cicadas in the eastern US, each appearing in different years. But why are #cicadas so freakin' loud? Entomologist Samuel Ramsey has the answers.

Watch the full video at www.youtube.com/WIRED

node.text:
At first glance, these photos of models swimming with whale sharks off the coast of the Philippines appear heavily Photoshopped. But while the levels and colors have been manipulated and the backgrounds tweaked, the most striking part – the models' proximity to sharks – is real.

The photos went viral after hitting the internet and led to a new awareness of the at-risk whale shark species. That was the photographers' plan all along. 

Read more about this stunning whale shark series at the link in the bio.

📸: Shawn Heinrichs

node.text:
Autonomous killer robots now look like more of a foregone conclusion in the future of warfare than ever before. 

The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, a division of the Pentagon, is currently conducting experiments involving dozens of ground and aerial robots operating in simulated urban warfare scenarios. The results so far suggest that human commanders will have almost no chance of outsmarting fast-moving swarms of machines—and that putting decision-making in the hands of our own lethal robots may be the best option for mitigating casualties.

Read about the shift in the Pentagon’s thinking regarding autonomous weapons at the link in our bio.

On this day in 1969, the world watched with bated breath as Apollo 11 took flight for the moon. The mission would alter the course of human history—changing what was possible and what could be if we did it together. But it all nearly turned to tragedy when the guidance computer continuously crashed while astronauts Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin struggled to touch down on the lunar surface. Read the full story of how this iconic moment nearly didn't happen at the link in the bio. 

📸: NASA

node.text:
15 years ago today, a young app called Twitter launched with the goal of changing how people communicate online. But what started as a fun app for socializing gave way to something bigger: it became a voice for the voiceless, and Black Twitter was born.

The ingenious use of the app by Black users created a ripple effect that resulted in the creation of Black community and empowerment. More than a decade later, Black Twitter has become the most dynamic subset not only of Twitter but of the wider social internet—capable of creating, shaping, and remixing popular culture at lightspeed.

Head to the link in bio to take in the very first chronicling of one of the internet's most powerful communities.
